ink almost everybody agrees on the "q" part being 64<br />bits, but that may just be me not having seen it in any other context.<br /><br />And before anybody points it out - yes, we already have lots of uses<br />of "dword" in various places. But they tend to be mostly<br />hardware-specific - either architectures or drivers.<br /><br />So I'd _prefer_ to try to keep "word" and "dword" away from generic<br />helper routines. But it's not like anything is really black and white.<br /><br />           Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
